And there's something coming up on the thing about looking at Indian history, and something about terms in Indian history. And I think that part of that, yeah, problematizing the term of traditional culture. Because a lot of the modern artwork that's being made by Indians is traditionally based, but maybe not like beaded tennis shoes or something like that with traditional designs on it. It's like, how do you define that? And how does the market define that? So we live in a market-driven economy. And Indian art is just like any other commodity. So we have to deal with that. Maybe with that, we'll let people comment during lunch and during the breaks and things to Terry. I thought that was great. So thank you. That's our plan for right now. Our next speaker is Jacob Manitoul-Bailey, second, Fox, and I wish Jacob were an American Studies major. He's taken a lot of courses in American Studies. But unfortunately, he was seduced by the Community Studies Board because they would allow him to do a six-month field internship. And he's going to be going to Oklahoma to work with the Sac and Fox at the end of the spring quarter. Is that right? He won't be back until the first of the year. And he's been involved in a number of things. A number of projects on campus, and one of the most important has to do with the repatriation process at UC Santa Cruz. He has been doing an internship and has learned a great deal about art collections, probably the second most knowledgeable person on the campus right now about the small collection that we have of Indian remains at UC Santa Cruz, and has also taken it. And he's going to be doing some of the research on this in his own characteristically intellectual way, and raising some very broad questions about the relationship, both institutional and intellectual, between the discipline of anthropology and the American Indian community. And so he has a number of interesting points to raise. He's going to talk about the whole repatriation situation at UCSC. So, Jacob? One of my nicknames for Terri is Boss. And I tell you that because I'm going to be following a lot of what she said in what I want to discuss today. And repatriation, as it has been defined, stands for, and this is a legal definition, the return of sacred objects, human remains. Unassociated funerary goods and items of cultural patrimony to American Indian nations. And repatriation currently is largely discussed within the terms and defined within the terms of NAGPRA, which is the Native American Graves Repatriation and Protection Act, which was passed in 1990. And I say I want to follow Terri because I want to talk a little bit more about this. I want to follow Terri because I want to talk about images, stereotypes, assumptions, responsibility, a lot of the same issues. And I also want to follow her by starting with a story about my mother. Because my mother went, when my mother was going to school, there was no such thing as Native American studies. There was no such thing as Indian education. If you wanted to have anything to do with Indians in the college setting, you went into anthropology. And a lot of Indians went into anthropology. And some of them made it. And a lot more didn't make it. And my mom was one of those. She dropped out of college. And I grew up with stories about the crazy things that anthropologists thought about Indians and the even sicker things that they did to our dead. And when I was a little girl, I was a little girl. When I first started, and I'm really glad that there's a lot of anthropology students on this sheet. Maybe we can get a little dialogue going here because I have a lot of problems. I've always grown up with a lot of assumptions and a lot of stereotypes about anthropologists. And when I first started researching repatriation, I uncovered horror story after horror story about past and current anthropological practice. And it reinforced a lot of the ideas I had about anthropology and what it does and what it has done to Indian people. And at the same time, I've had sort of a morbid fascination with the strange creatures and sort of the rituals that they seem to love to carry out. And those were the terms that I would have thought about anthropology and anthropologists when I started interning at the University of California, Santa Cruz Archaeological Collection. The repatriation debate, and I shouldn't use the word debate. I shouldn't even use the word movement. I should use the word war because that's the way that both a lot of natives and a lot of non-natives, writing about repatriation, have defined it. They've defined it as a war. As a war of science versus religion, a war of objective, cold, analytical anthropologists versus warm, spiritual Indians. And a lot of the titles of articles written by both natives and non-natives, a lot of prominent people are things like science, or sacrilege, disputing the dead, preservation or reburial, Native Americans versus American museums, a battle for artifacts. And so this is the mindset that prevails in a lot of places. And it was the mindset that I had when I started interning at the anthropology department. That was an extremely difficult process for me. You know? You walk in. You walk into this building. It's called Social Sciences I. I normally refer to it as the evil building. And it's this big concrete monolith. You know, you walk up two stairs of floor, the air starts to get stale. The posters start to appear on the wall. Paleolithic culture and plains material items in the faunal area. You know, people are talking in languages that I can't understand. And I get to the fourth floor, where they keep the bodies. And I start getting pretty whacked out. When I first started my internship, I could only think of things in either or situations. It was either I go in there and I lay my agenda out on the table, or I hide it. And I compromise my sense of integrity. And every situation that I found myself in was a set of either or statements, neither of which I was happy with. And eventually, what I was forced to do for my own sanity and to get anywhere in working to help the repatriation process was that I had to go out on a limb. I had to put myself out there. And I had to explain to my supervisor, who's an archaeologist, and my co-worker, who is an archaeology student, that I had a lot of fear and a lot of anger about what was going on. And I was amazed. I was absolutely amazed at the emotional responses that I got from those people and what they told me about. how they felt and how they had become sick, how they felt forces, and how hard it was for them to be involved in such a thing. And we really begin to build bridges to facilitate a way of thinking about repatriation that wasn't us versus them. It wasn't me carrying a banner going in there to get rid of anthropology. And I think that Indians have a lot of stereotypes about anthropologists, anthropologists have a lot of stereotypes about Indians, and the dominant society has stereotypes about both of them. Which feed into a rhetoric which divides us. And this is when it comes to survival and when it comes to responsibility, like Terry was talking about, is that anthropologists, the most of them, when I really sit down and talk with them, the basic thing that comes out is that they love Indians. That they love Indians. That they feel a responsibility towards Indians. That the whole reason they went into their field is because they wanted to help Indians. And they got into the field and then they found out that they had to do these certain things, which wasn't what they thought. And they ended up interacting with objects and with remains and not with live human beings. And repatriation has forced a lot of anthropologists, and a lot of Indians, to get over their fear about each other and to come together to work on projects. To try to resolve this crisis. And anthropologists, and I use the term so generally and so broadly, and I refer to such a huge group of people. But there's a narrative that's emerging which is trying to succeed the one that's of us versus them, which says we can work together, and we can work together to do some important things. So that's the first sort of issue I want to pose. The second issue I want to pose is about how the rhetoric around repatriation talks about Indians. And about how they feel about spirits, and their ancestors, and desecration, and things like this in a way that really disturbs me. And it disturbs me because it's not tribally specific, and it's not guided by that. And so I think for instance... there's a National NAGPRA Committee, and they have field meetings which are help to formulate policy and at one of these field meetings there was a presentation which represented the Indian viewpoint for that segment, and the people who got up there activists and they basically said that you know all these bones need to go back in the ground and we don't care what they are we don't care if they're Chinese we don't care if they're Jewish we don't care what tribe they are there's the spirits have been disturbed the spirits have been disturbed and we need to put them at peace and repatriation was an inner tribal movement to deal with some very serious issues dangerous dangerous issues powerful issues things that I don't possibly understand and, my solution is to look to the people in my community like I'm going for six months and I'm not gonna go back now, the history of the basically of regional to intern with the Sac and Fox Repatriation Committee, which is made up of elders. And their response is that they need to move extremely slow. They need to be extremely careful because they're dealing with very powerful and dangerous issues and that they need to be guided by the traditional beliefs and the traditional ways that have guided them in everything else they do. And what I see going on a lot of other places is these remains, these ancestors, become a war trophy. We will get these bones back from you anthropologists. We will take them and put them in the ground. We will take them and put them in the ground where they belong. And that attitude, I don't know what to think about it because I don't know where it's coming from. And I have a lot of documentation that I've been finding lately. For instance, there was this case in Kentucky. We had a place called Slag Farm and 1,200 Shawnee bodies were taken out of the ground by pot hunters. And Indian people immediately responded because of the desecration. But in addition to ceremonies. They put to rebury those people a proposal for $157,000 to bring 700 elders of the International Elders Council came up. A local news story forecasted up to 100,000 Indians could be expected to show up for the reburial. The Evansville Convention and Visitors Bureau sent out housing forms to all tribal offices. Because they expected huge crowds to materialize. Members of the reburial committee started claiming that it would be the largest gathering of tribal hierarchy this century. A concert was proposed. A pow wow. A sidewalk art show. Hollywood stars would arrive according to one of the organizers of the festival. They're here, I'm here. I'm here. I'm here. I'm here. I'm here. the event. It became an event. And these are Indian people. Eventually, two of the organizers took off with $30,000 that they'd raised. And nowhere could I find that the Shawnee had had anything to do with this. So, I think James was passing me a little note here. And I'll stop right there. That's great. What questions do people have? I'm sort of wondering about whether you actually believe it's wrong for groups who aren't directly affiliated with these remains to lobby for their reburial. And the example I think of is a few years back, a group of Indian tribes from southern New England reburied the remains of some Niantic Indians. There are no, there is no Niantic tribe extent today. And, you know, the Indians were buried on the Pequot Reservation. The tribal medicine man of the Wampanoag Indians and the medicine man of the I think it was the Passamaquoddy were presiding over the ceremony. And they were buried these remains in a very pan-tribal manner. They didn't necessarily do it in the authentic Niantic way, whatever that was. But they at least returned these things to the ground, which they knew was the tradition of the Niantics to actually bury the remains. But had they not done that, these remains would have stayed in a museum or wherever they were forever, because there would have been no Niantics to claim them back. The National Committee, their basic and this is of course rumor because I have not personally talked to the National Committee, but the grapevine says that the National Committee, which is made up of I think four Indians and three non-Indians, is saying that any Native American is closer to a human remain that's of Native American descent than any non-Indian is. And consequently we will act on that prerogative. Now if there are remains which have no tribal affiliation, I don't know what to do about that. I don't have an answer for you. But what I'm saying is that a lot of people are saying, we're tired of waiting. We want to do this now. No more consultation. No more discussing it. We want those bones back in the ground. And my concern with that is that when I talk to tribal elders, they're saying we need to take this very slow. We need to be very careful. We need to have a lot of discussion. We need, the Sac and Fox Repatriation Policy, I have it with me, says that we need the opinion of every single member of the tribe. And we need all of their knowledge because no one can handle this alone. This needs to be a collective pursuit, a collective effort. And so when a rash decision is made, and I'll use an example which strikes close to home, and I'll use it without names, but this University, Stanford, did a repatriation several years ago of Ohlone individuals. And it's unclear what type of consultation process happened, but there are Ohlone individuals today who will not talk to other Ohlone individuals because of the way that reburial was handled. Because the people who ended up receiving the remains to put them in the earth carried out ceremonies in a way that they found to be spiritual violence. And the words that they used was that it reminded them of when the Nazis buried Jews in mass graves. And all they could do was go home and pray and purify themselves. Now I don't know if that individual speaks for the traditional Ohlones. I don't know anything about it. All I know is that if someone had been more careful, had taken longer to engage in a process to make sure that there was unity in the tribe on how to move forward on this, then there wouldn't be that issue. And for me, it's like, it's so dangerous and Indian people have waited so long to have this that a few more years to work out some problems among you isn't going to hurt anything. To wait even three or four years until your tribe or your community or whatever has come to a consensus on how to handle the issue and has designated people specifically to handle these matters, then that's better than rushing it. It's not an issue that can be rushed. Do you think they can actually achieve that sort of unanimity? Well, I don't know about all tribes. The Sac and Fox, I think, are going to from the way it's going. The Hopi, for instance, they have four archaeologists who work for them. They have an archaeological program and it's overseen by 18 clan elders and priests. Now, I don't know how the Hopi feel about that, but it sounds like something that's better than giving up bones or sacred objects when there is still some doubt about who should be receiving those. Repatriation, and this is my personal opinion, is not an activist issue. This is not primarily a political issue. It's primarily a spiritual issue and a cultural issue. And it's not something to carry banners around about. There is a proper way which needs to be directed by people who have knowledge. I don't know. I don't know how to handle a repatriation and I would never go do that. Can I just chip in here? Because I think it's a really good question and obviously, as you know, there are also a great number of remains which aren't even tribally identified, whether they still exist as a community or not. So this is going to be a continual problem. It seems to me that one way of answering this that's suggested is that I think what Jacob has done very well is he's developing a distinction between responsibility and ownership. And what he's trying to do is to show why those two things being very different have very different implications for how this is handled, whether it's on a tribal or an intertribal level. I think he's trying to suggest that if the bones are approached as something which is owned over which there can be a political battle, then it doesn't matter whether it's a tribe doing it or whether it's the National Congress of American Indians. You're going to run into inappropriate potentials, potential for inappropriate kinds of things. of actions. If it's approached as a problem of responsibility rather than of ownership, then again, there can be appropriate solutions to either tribal or intertribal problems that come up in the repatriation process. Personally, I don't have any problem with the propriety of these people because I see that as an example of taking responsibility. Now whether within their own rhetoric they viewed it as a political battle and they approached it as something they owned, I don't know. But I'm saying that it suggests a model of responsibility rather than of ownership. And it seems to me that's one really important thing I'm learning out of your work is how to understand those issues. And maybe I should be more specific. In terms of the law, one of the ways that institutions determine who they repatriate remains to is they look at the ICC map, which is the Indian Claims Commission map, which is a map that is only accurate for certain periods of time and has a lot to do with the political influence and the legal influence of the tribes who took cases before the Indian Claims Commission. For example, the Siouxs have a huge area on the map. And if that's the map that they're using and then they go ahead and repatriate to the Siouxs without doing any other further consultation and it comes up later on that they have more documentation that says that those belong to another tribe or something like that, it can cause division within the community as well as a huge public relations problem for the institution. I have a couple comments. I was on the repatriation committee at Berkeley when I was a student there and it was a war. Because it was Indian and non-Indian on that committee and we battled every meeting. And I have a box full of the material that we produced and had to read in addition to all of our classes. So it's not an easy solution because division, not in my tribe in Oklahoma but the Seminole tribe in Florida, they found some remains in northern Florida by Tampa. And as Seminoles were most likely descendants of those remains, they contacted the tribe and asked them if they wanted to have that. So James Billy, the tribal chairman went up there and said, yes, I want to take this land and turn it into trust land because it's our bones. And then he immediately put a bingo pardon there because the land was turned to trust land. Now that's caused tremendous division in the nation down there. The repercussions are still being felt. And some people said, how could he take an area that was sacred and remains? I mean, he didn't do it right on the burial ground. But certainly it's very difficult to take land and turn it into trust land. The government is very unwilling to do that at this point. And I haven't checked recently because I've been broiled in the Seminole nation in Oklahoma right now. But what is happening, too, is that it's causing division for the people in there who have questions about that. So when I get the paper from down there, they're still asking. And James said, I always intended to do this. You just didn't understand that this was my idea in the beginning because you have people saying, how could you set up a bingo and get another bingo pardon, even though it does bring in tremendous revenues and it's another consistent matter. But it isn't a simple answer. And certainly the very fact that the Seminole nation isn't even formed until after contact has another ramification in it for those people to approve the most likely descendants. It is problematic right now. One more and then we'll take this. I just want to comment. I also, like I said, I'm new to Stanford, but I'm also one of the MAGPA people that have been invited as part of that group to participate. We've only met a couple times and they talked about the Maloney Patriotation and how they put into more of that. But it's interesting that people felt that way because, you know, I serve on that committee and I'm the only Indian on there. There used to be two of us, but the woman's gone. But, you know, I can only speak for, you know, what I believe in and what I think, you know, I know about my tribe. Sometimes it's very difficult when you ask. You know, I don't speak, you know, I don't represent the Indian voice of all Indian tribes. But certainly I'll try to do my best that I can to talk about, you know, you mentioned about the sacred and all that kind of stuff. Yes, and so forth. That's a big issue for me because, you know, I come from a Pueblo that's very, you know, very still traditional. And a whole lot of these things are sacred. And I've seen Victor's film. When you were reading that article about the Kentucky, it was interesting because a couple years ago, Amos received a lot of there were no bones or anything, bodies, but a lot of Smithsonian a lot of sacred islands that had been taken. And the news people in Albuquerque were just, you know, really wanted you know, to come in and document and film the whole thing. And it was just, it was just really crazy. But it was like the same thing as a Hopi. There was our priests and our clan leaders and those people that were involved in this whole thing. And the governors made an appearance at the airport, you know, just to do it quick. So the press were here blah, blah, blah, and we're going home. And that was it. We didn't allow anybody back on the reservation. And then once we, you know, the items were brought to the reservation, they just brought them into the plaza, straight into the Casici's house, and that was it. There was no, we still don't know to this day what was there. But that's not for us to do. You know, because our leadership, our religious leaders, they did the appropriate things when they brought these things home. And people you know, they were like, well, can we display these and we can take, you know, the news people take a picture. And we just, you know, it was, I think it was very appropriately done. I don't know what those items are, but I don't question it because I know the right thing was done from the leadership. Everybody's happy. And I think that's what's important, and I think we've all heard those things. I'd say we're off to a great start this morning. Let's thank Jacob and then we'll... . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . Thank you. Thank you.
